[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Keep the charge",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—The main charge to Solomon is noble enough. He is to “show himself a man,” in spite of his youth; he is to take heed in all things to follow the Law of the Lord; he is to trust both in the general promise of God to obedience, and in the special promise made to the house of David (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 7:12-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is remarkably in harmony with the beautiful Psalm, “the last words of David,” preserved in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 23:3-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", telling how “he that ruleth over men must be just, ruling in the fear of God,” and, in spite of consciousness of shortcomings from this high ideal, trusting in the “everlasting covenant of God” with him, “ordered in all things, and sure.” Nor does it accord less with the equally beautiful prayer of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 29:18-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for Solomon and for the people. In all this David speaks in the spirit of a true servant and saint of God. But in the special charges that follow we see the worldly prudence of the old statesman, and in one case some trace of long-remembered grudge, singularly true to imperfect human nature, although utterly unworthy of an ideal picture of a hero-king.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Kings 2:3-4",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 2:3-4",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And keep the charge of the Lord thy God — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Here we find David inculcating, in his last moments, the great ruling principle; the foundation-stone of the Hebrew state, and which in some measure distinguishes it from all other governments that have ever subsisted. For the whole strength and stability of that state was built, not upon the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "riches ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "forces ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "of the kingdom, but upon a strict observance of the statutes and commandments of the Lord. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "As it is written in the law of Moses — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which the prince was enjoined to transcribe and read, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) that he might govern his own and his people’s actions by it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "That thou mayest prosper — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "behave thyself prudently. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hereby he intimates that religion is the truest reason of state, and that all true wisdom and good success depend upon piety. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "That the Lord may confirm his word — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Fulfil his promise, the condition upon which it was suspended being performed. Thus, to engage him to keep the charge of the Lord, he represents unto him the gracious promise which God had made him, to perpetuate the kingdom in his family without interruption, provided his children sincerely and heartily cleaved to God in faithful and conscientious obedience to his commandments.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2:1-4 David's charge to Solomon is, to keep the charge of the Lord. The authority of a dying father is much, but nothing to that of a living God. God promised David that the Messiah should come from his descendants, and that promise was absolute; but the promise, that there should not fail of them a man on the throne of Israel, was conditional; if he walks before God in sincerity, with zeal and resolution: in order hereunto, he must take heed to his way.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The \"statutes\" have been explained to be the positive ordinances of the Law; the \"commandments\" the moral precepts, not to steal, etc.; the \"judgments\" the laws belonging to civil government; and the \"testimonies\" the laws directing the commemoration of certain events. Compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 19:7-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3. keep the charge of the Lord thy God—that is, the divine law in all its ceremonial as well as moral requirements. But particular reference was intended to its political institutions, as it was only by strictly maintaining the conduct that became the Hebrew monarch (De 17:10-20), that he would secure the blessing of peace and prosperity to his reign (see on [288]De 4:5; [289]De 29:10).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
