  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "And keep the {b} charge of the LORD thy God, to walk in his ways, to keep his statutes, and his commandments, and his judgments, and his testimonies, as it is written in the law of Moses, that thou mayest prosper in all that thou doest, and whithersoever thou turnest thyself:",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And keep the ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cverse3",
            "text": "{b}",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " charge of the LORD thy God, to walk in his ways, to keep his statutes, and his commandments, and his judgments, and his testimonies, as it is written in the law of Moses, that thou mayest prosper in all that thou doest, and whithersoever thou turnest thyself:",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(b) He shows how hard it is to govern and that no one can do it well except he obey God.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "keep the charge of the Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The word rendered ‘charge’ here has no connexion with the verb used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but is the customary expression in the Book of Numbers for the care and oversight of the Tabernacle and other things committed to the Levites. (See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 1:53",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 3:7-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " &c.) It is used also of other sacred offices and the duties attached thereto. Thus is imported into the word a solemn signification, though in etymology it is connected with the word which precedes it, rendered ‘keep’.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to keep his statutes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "his commandments, and his judgements",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] These words appear to refer to the three portions of the divine law, the ceremonial, the moral, and the judicial ordinances revealed by God in the Mosaic code; while ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "testimonies",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " may be interpreted of those evidences of God’s will towards man which are made clear by His dealings with bygone generations. Thus God in His word bears witness to Himself.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "written in the law of Moses",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The allusion is to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:18-20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the king, in time to come, is bidden to keep a copy of the Law, and to study it, that so his days may be prolonged.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And keep the charge",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [lit., \"watch the watch\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "custodies custodiam Jehovae",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or, \"serve the service.\" Bahr paraphrases, \"be a true watcher in the service of Jehovah.\" The words are constantly employed to denote a strict performance of the service of the tabernacle or of the duties of the priests and Levites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 8:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 18:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 1:53",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 3:7, 8, 25, 28, 32, 38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 31:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 23:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"The reference,\" says Rawlinson, \"is to the charge given to all the kings in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:18-20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".\" But there is no necessity for restricting it to that one injunction. What the charge is is explained presently] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "of the Lord thy God to walk in His ways, to keep",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [same word] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
